post_text: To support and preserve the safety of our staff and families, we will not be offering meal service or tech service today (9/9). Schools are closed through 9/11. Our campuses are still open to evacuees and we will be continuing to support our community at these sites. We will continue to update you on changes. #estacadastrong

Our campuses are still open to evacuees and we will be continuing to support our community at these sites. We will continue to update you on changes. #estacadastrong

post_text: School will be closed through Friday 9/11 due to weather/fire hazards. We will be focused on serving our community through use of our facilities to evacuees and more. Meal delivery routes will continue as scheduled through Friday, and our tech office at EHS will be open to serve families experiencing tech difficulties. Tonight's Canvas session will be rescheduled, and will be made available on our website.
text: School will be closed through Friday 9/11 due to weather/fire hazards. We will be focused on serving our community through use of our facilities to evacuees and more. Meal delivery routes will continue as scheduled through Friday, and our tech office at EHS will be open to serve families experiencing tech difficulties. Tonight's Canvas session will be rescheduled, and will be made available on our website.

post_text: Meal deliveries will arrive at homes today 3 hours later than your student's school pickup time (on the same schedule as spring). Routes adjusted for weather and road conditions are: Route 14 (Casper) past Silver Fox, Route 3 (Mickey Mouse) past Crane Rd., and Route 2 Batman past Judd Rd. Routes within 1.5 miles of school will not be run this year. Pickup sites will be open at Wade Creek Park from 9-10, and the Estacada Fire Dept. from 10-11. We can't wait to see and serve you!

post_text: We can’t wait to start school again tomorrow. With power outages in our area this evening, we will be monitoring outages tonight and tomorrow morning. We’ll contact you early tomorrow morning if anything changes with our back to school plan. If you don’t hear from us, that means things are running according to schedule, and we hope you have a great first day of school!

post_text:
April 16th will be the last day of school for many of our Estacada High School seniors. We are so proud of their accomplishments. At 8:20 pm on April 16th our stadium lights will be on for 20 minutes to recognize their achievement. To allow this event to occur and to keep everyone safe, we have some important guidelines and information:

- We ask that all community members that attend this event stay inside their vehicles at all times.
- We will be live streaming and taking photos to allow many families to stay at home and still celebrate.
- We ask that everyone is mindful of social distancing at all times. Our campuses and grounds are still closed to the public at all times.

Thank you for your cooperation and for your support of our accomplished and resilient Class of 2020.

post_text:
We continue to be humbled by our community’s support as we work to serve all students during our closure. Estacada’s community churches worked together and just delivered three weeks worth of food to be sent home with our students signed up for our Backpack Buddies program.

We will also be running our regular bus routes (on a 3 hour delay schedule) and dropping off free food for all students during the closure. We will have two food sites for food pickup as well: Wade Creek Park from 9:30-10:15 and the parking lot by the Estacada Fire Station from 10:30-11:15. This is available for all Estacada School District children 18 and under.

We do not need food donations at this time, we need our community to please SPREAD THE WORD that resources are available. Details: http://www.estacada.k12.or.us/cms/One.aspx?portalId=122600&pageId=49822397

post_text:
On Saturday a young member of the Estacada community passed away. The Estacada School District's thoughts will continue to be with this family, and we offer our deepest condolences.

Our entire district is grieved by this sudden loss. Estacada School District staff are supporting students at school by providing spaces and opportunities to talk, grieve, and meet with counseling staff. Impacted families are encouraged to reach out if their students may need additional support at this time. Providing support for our students and staff remains a top priority as our community experiences this loss.

post_text: Through advocating for student safety, and our partnership with the City of Estacada - Government- we were happy to bring on School Resource Officer Russell last year. Excited for another year of building positive relationships between law enforcement and our students.
shared_text:
Clackamas County Sheriff's Office
September 4, 2019 at 2:03 PM ·

Today, as #BackToSchoolWeek continues, let’s meet another of our School Resource Officers:

Deputy Jonah Russell, our SRO at Estacada High School!

Deputy Russell takes time to connect with the students at Estacada High in many ways — including running #football drills on the playground. He’s a member of our SWAT team, served in the military, and played college and arena football. He helps out w/ EHS athletics today.

Deputy Russell also made national headlines last year as one of the deputies who helped save Baby Audrey last year after she stopped breathing at a mall photo studio. He later visited the recovering baby at OHSU. You can read this incredible story here:
https://www.clackamas.us/sheriff/2018-10-09-CCSOPR-CPRBabySave.html

Welcome back, Deputy Russell!

Tomorrow we’ll meet another SRO during #BackToSchool week.

#BackToSchool2019

The district's brand new buses- Bus 40 and Bus 41- have arrived and are ready to report for duty! 🚌🚌🚌

Annually, the Estacada School District purchases two new buses in order to comply with Senate Bill 1008 (which requires the district's oldest buses to be replaced by 2025), and to help ensure that our students are transported safely.

shared_text:
City of Estacada - Government
May 30, 2019 at 8:47 AM ·

The City of Estacada Public Works Department will be conducting smoke tests of sanitary sewers in the following communities the week of June 3rd:

Lake Shore Area
Northwest area of Estacada
Ginseng Area

These tests will assist us in locating breaks and defects in the sewer system. During the test, YOU MAY SEE SMOKE COMING FROM VENT STACKS ON BUILDINGS OR FROM HOLES IN THE GROUND. Don’t be alarmed. The smoke has no odor, is non-toxic, non-staining, does not create a fire hazard, and will dissipate in a few minutes.

Before we conduct the smoke test, please pour water into your basement floor drains and into any unused sinks. This will seal the drain traps so that smoke will not enter your building through the drain.

If smoke should enter your building during the test, it probably means that there are defects in the plumbing that could allow DANGEROUS SEWER GAS to enter. Note the location of the smoke and call Tom Seal, Public Works Director at 503-630-8270, x205 to arrange a meeting with our inspector. You may open doors and windows to ventilate any smoke that enters the building.

shared_text:
The Clackamas Bookshelf
April 23, 2019 at 7:57 AM ·

Question: Where is the Clackamas Bookshelf now?

Answer: Estacada!

We visited both elementary schools in Estacada, giving away over 1500 books in one day! Each student chose two books to take home.

After clarifying that they got to keep them, one student gleefully said “now I have THREE books!” We sure love what we do. ❤️

Our friend and board member Erika Spooner was there dishing out books too. Thank goodness!! That a busy day!

In the two weeks since our announcement, we now have only 10 remaining spots. This is a great opportunity for four-year-old children in our community, and tuition assistance is available. We are also happy to announce that we will be partnering with Champions Before and After School to provide daycare opportunities at River Mill Elementary, beginning this summer!

Questions? Drop them in the comments below!

post_text:
Estacada School District is launching “Virtual School Days.” On days when school is closed due to weather, students will now participate in learning opportunities from home. This initiative is designed to close the learning gap that occurs when students stay home for the day, provide a unique learning opportunity, and may reduce the number of makeup days at the end of the year. There will be accommodations made for families that do not have access to the internet or computers.

The district and your building principal have sent out an email with details on this new initiative, and Superintendent Carpenter will be hosting a Facebook Live event to answer questions at 4:00 pm today. Learn more at estacada.k12.or.us.

This month's townhall topic is the Estacada School District budget. We owe our taxpayers a transparent explanation of how funds are being spent. We also are excited to provide an opportunity for our community to ask questions.

Tune in on our Facebook page at 7:00pm tonight (January 17th).

post_text:
District staff, students, teachers, and parents are coming together to discuss what our school schedule should look like for the next four years. Join the conversation this afternoon at 2:45 at our second Facebook Live calendar conversation.

Can't make it? Post a question in our Facebook Live comments section at any time, and get a response within 24 hours. All community input is being documented and integrated into the consideration process. The school board will vote on the proposed school calendar in the spring of 2019.

Together we will work towards finding the best school schedule options for student achievement in the Estacada School District!

post_text:
Estacada Middle School students have started a group called YANA (You Are Not Alone), to address bullying and add to the culture of kindness being built in their school. Other students are welcome to sign up and join in, and donation jars to support this new group are located around town.

#estacadapride
shared_text:
Estacada Middle School
December 11, 2018 at 11:56 AM ·

WHAT IS YANA??

YANA stands for “You are not alone.” It is a program started by three Estacada Middle School students. They started YANA after they heard hate comments being made to people around the school. The purpose of YANA is to end bullying and promote kindness around EMS. YANA has already received a donation of $100 and won an award from the city of Estacada as “Students of the Year”. They are going to eventually have YANA t-shirts for sale and will be having meetings for the club members, along with surprises and missions for them to help make our school a better place. If your student (who goes to EMS) is interested in signing up, there is a sign up sheet on Ms. Wexler’s office door. Also remind your student that wearing yellow on Friday supports YANA. They accept donations and have jars set up around local businesses to help raise some money to fund our shirts, ect. We openly welcome any student interested in joining and want them to know that they aren’t alone. :)

Families: Before we know it, snow days will be arriving! We notify families of snow closures and delays as early as possible (around 5:30 AM) via our website, Flash Alert, local news stations, social media, and phone texts and calls. In order to get phone notifications, please ensure that we have updated contact information on file for you!

How to do this: go to https://powerschool.estacada.k12.or.us/public/home.html to update your contact information online, or contact your child's school office for assistance.

Have you updated your information but are still having trouble receiving communications? Please reach out to us at communications@estacada.k12.or.us. We are here to help!

Estacada High School metals students are building a path from their classroom to the metal shop. The area has become muddy and over trafficked, so students saw it as an opportunity to get some hands-on work experience while improving their school and classroom.

Their teacher - Mr. Richards - noted that "our program is about developing skills, and it's also about developing good workers. I want to help develop workers that take instruction and take initiative".

Career Technical Education continues to be a priority and a valuable resource and opportunity in the Estacada School District. #CareerTechnicalEducationWorks

October 10, 2018 at 9:45 AM ·

This morning, EMS students practiced a "lockout" drill. During a lockout, exterior doors are locked. Classrooms continue to teach during a lockout. Drills are regularly practiced at all Estacada schools to ensure that students and staff are prepared in case of emergency.

Clackamas Education Service District was live.
October 3, 2018 at 4:50 PM ·

From 6 to 8 pm tonight - What are the top challenges facing Oregon schools, and what steps will state leaders do to address them?

Met with Clackamas County Sheriff's Office this morning during their Coffee With a Cop event to discuss how they can serve and protect our schools and students.

Join our conversation on school safety during our community townhall session on October 18th!

post_text:
Through partnering with the Oregon Food Bank, the Estacada School District is excited to offer a weekly food bank for all Estacada School District families in need.

Please share this information to ensure that all families that may need support are aware of this new resource in our district!
